cs.SI, cs.CY, cs.CR, cs.SOC, cs.CL

This paper is likely to belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category as it analyzes the behavior of state-sponsored actors on social media platforms. It could also belong to cs.CY (Computers and Society) as it discusses the impact of these actors on the Web's information ecosystem. Additionally, it could be categorized under cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) as it deals with the manipulation of public opinion and potential threats to national security. It could also be classified under cs.SOC (Social and Behavioral Sciences) as it studies the behavior of individuals and groups in online communities. Finally, it could be categorized under cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it involves the analysis of natural language used by these state-sponsored actors.
